yable. </span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I undertook to consider if there were any points it would be appropriate for us to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">make in relation to the questions you are asking in the inquiry. Decisions as to whether </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">we should have a written constitution, and what it should cover, are ultimately political in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">nature, and I offer no comment on that issue.</span></p><p style="margin:14.4pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.15pt">Lady Hale, the Deputy President of the Court, and I however feel that there is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">one issue we would wish to draw to your attention. That is whether, in the event of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.2pt">there being a written constitution for the United Kingdom, a separate Constitutional </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Court would be required.</span></p><p style="margin:12.6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">Whilst it is the practice in many civil law countries to have separate Supreme </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">Courts and Constitutional Courts (and sometimes also separate Supreme Administrative </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">Courts), that is not the pattern in common-law 'Countries. Rather, the practice is for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">constitutional issues to be considered by the Supreme Court. That would certainly be the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">model we would prefer. It works perfectly well in countries whose judicial systems are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">very similar to ours, such as Canada. Indeed, we already perform a constitutional role, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">both in the Supreme Court (albeit to a limited extent) and the Judicial Committee of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.05pt">Privy Council. At least at the moment it is difficult to estimate what effect it might have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.1pt">on our workload (and hence whether or not there would be a need for more Justices).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The other issue which needs to be looked at very carefully is whether it should be possible for GovernmentÂ  or Parliament to make references to the Supreme Court as to the constitutionality of proposed legislation, either before it has been introduced to Parliament or after it has been passed by Parliament, but not yet come into force.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-